Overall Flow
Lambda Entry Point (lambda_handler)

The function is triggered by an SNS event.
It logs the incoming event and then parses the SNS message (JSON) to extract alarm information.
Extracting the Alarm Name and Tags

The code retrieves the AlarmName from the parsed alarm info.
It then calls list_tags_for_resource using the alarm’s ARN to get any associated tags.
Next, parse_alarm_name_and_tags is invoked:
It examines the alarm’s name suffix (e.g., -scale-up or -scale-down) to determine the scaling direction (Up or Down).
It also extracts the tag named "LastScaledTimestamp", if present.
Logging is done to confirm the parsed alarm names, the scaling action, and the last scaled timestamp.
Determining the Kinesis Stream Name

The get_stream_name function is called with the alarm info.
It looks into alarm_info["Trigger"]["Metrics"] for metrics with IDs "m1" or "m2".
Within those metrics, it searches the dimensions for one where the key is "name" (lowercase) and the value is "StreamName".
When found, it returns the stream name (e.g., "Kinesis-Scaling-AutoScalingStream01-lHrj7jDw9F3Q").
If not found, an error is logged and the function returns None.
Timestamp Check for Valid Scaling Event

The handler calls check_last_scaled_timestamp with the last scaled timestamp (if any) and the alarm’s StateChangeTime.
This function converts both timestamps into datetime objects.
It checks whether the new alarm event is more recent than the last scaling event and whether the event occurs after a “cooldown” period.
If the check fails, the handler sets the alarm’s state to INSUFFICIENT_DATA (via set_alarm_state) and returns early.
Retrieving Current Shard Count & Calculating New Shard Count

The code calls describe_stream_summary on the Kinesis client using the stream name to get the current shard count.
Then, calculate_new_shard_count is invoked with the current shard count and the scaling action:
For a scale-up request ("Up"), it doubles the shard count.
For a scale-down request ("Down"), it halves the shard count (ensuring it never falls below 1; if it reaches 1, it sets the down threshold to -1 to prevent further scale-down).
The new shard count and a potentially adjusted down threshold are returned and logged.
Dry Run Check

Before making any changes, the handler checks if DRY_RUN is enabled.
If true, the function logs that no scaling will be performed and exits.
Updating the Kinesis Stream

The handler calls update_shard_count on the Kinesis client with the stream name and the new shard count, using the 'UNIFORM_SCALING' option.
It then records the current time as alarm_last_scaled_timestamp (in UTC).
Updating CloudWatch Alarms

For the scale-up alarm:
The handler calls update_alarm with parameters including the new shard count, evaluation periods, datapoints, and threshold.
Then, set_alarm_state is called to set the state of the scale-up alarm to INSUFFICIENT_DATA, which resets its status.
For the scale-down alarm:
A similar process is followed with update_alarm (using a possibly adjusted down threshold and iterator age parameters) and then set_alarm_state.
Logging confirms that both alarms have been updated.
Tagging the Alarms

The handler calls get_alarm_arn to retrieve the ARNs of both the scale-up and scale-down alarms.
Then it calls tag_alarm for each alarm to update tags (such as ScaleAction, ComplimentaryAlarm, and LastScaledTimestamp) so that future scaling events can correctly reference when the last scaling occurred.
Logging confirms successful tagging.
Completion

Finally, the handler logs that scaling is complete for the stream and ends execution.
If any exception occurs during the process, it’s caught in the except block, logged with logger.exception, and then passed to error_handler which logs further details and emits a custom metric indicating a fatal error.
Summary of Method-by-Method Execution
lambda_handler(event, context)
→ Logs event; extracts alarm info.
→ Calls list_tags_for_resource to get alarm tags.
→ Calls parse_alarm_name_and_tags(tags_response, current_alarm_name) to determine scaling direction and get last scaling timestamp.
→ Calls get_stream_name(alarm_info) to extract the stream name.
→ Calls check_last_scaled_timestamp(last_scaled_timestamp, alarm_info.get("StateChangeTime", ""), 0) to verify event validity.
→ Retrieves current shard count with describe_stream_summary.
→ Calls calculate_new_shard_count(current_alarm_action, SCALE_DOWN_THRESHOLD, current_shard_count) to compute new shard count and threshold.
→ Checks DRY_RUN; if false, calls update_shard_count on the Kinesis client.
→ Captures the new scaling timestamp.
→ Calls update_alarm(...) twice (once for scale-up and once for scale-down) to update alarms.
→ Calls set_alarm_state(...) for both alarms to reset their state.
→ Calls get_alarm_arn(...) and then tag_alarm(...) to update alarm tags.
→ Logs that scaling is complete.

Helper Functions (update_alarm, set_alarm_state, etc.)
→ Each helper logs its entry, key operations, and exit.
→ They include retry logic for throttling errors and log each retry attempt.

Final Note
This detailed flow ensures that when an SNS-triggered CloudWatch alarm indicates that the stream usage has exceeded (or fallen below) the set thresholds, the Lambda function:

Correctly identifies the stream to be scaled,
Computes the new shard count based on the scaling direction,
Updates the Kinesis stream and reconfigures the alarms,
Tags the alarms with the latest scaling timestamp,
And logs each step for easy troubleshooting.
By following this process, you can trace the execution through the log messages and understand exactly how each helper function contributes to the overall scaling operation.
